1 Introduction to the data

1.1 Data and variables(see MS pg. 77,125)

Describe the data and the problem we wish to investigate.

We will be assessing different methods of detecting defects in software code written for NASA spacecraft instruments. The data contains 498 modules of software code written in âCâ language. The software code was evaluated, for defects and classified as âtrueâ (i.e., module has defective code) or âfalseâ (i.e., module has correct code). The SWDEFECTS file contains a variable that corresponds to each method. When the method predicts a defect, the corresponding variableâs value is âyesâ. Otherwise, it is ânoâ.

Using \(\LaTeX\) construct the formulae for

  1. Accuracy
  2. Detection rate
  3. False alarm rate
  4. Precision

Latex Example: See (http://www.stat.cmu.edu/~cshalizi/rmarkdown/#elements-of-math-mode)

\[ \begin{eqnarray} P(|X-\mu| > k) & = & P(|X-\mu|^2 > k^2)\\ & \leq & \frac{\mathbb{E}\left[|X-\mu|^2\right]}{k^2}\\ & \leq & \frac{\mathrm{Var}[X]}{k^2} \end{eqnarray} \] \[ \begin{eqnarray} P(Algorithm && is & correct) & = \frac {a+d} {a+b+c+d} \end{eqnarray} \] \[ \begin{eqnarray} P(predict && defect & | & module & has & defect) & = \frac {d} {b+d} \end{eqnarray} \] \[ \begin{eqnarray} P(predict && defect & | & module & has & no & defect) & = \frac {c} {a+c} \end{eqnarray} \] \[ \begin{eqnarray} P(module && has & defect & | & predict & defect) & = \frac {d} {c+d} \end{eqnarray} \]

2 R functions

Using the above definitions make R functions that will create the required probabilities, please remove eval=FALSE when creating the functions :

acc=function(a,b,c,d)
{
  isCorrect <- ((a+d)/(a+b+c+d))
  return(isCorrect)
  
}
detect=function(b,d)
{
  hasDefect <- (d/(b+d))
  return(hasDefect)
}
falarm=function(a,c)
{
  noDefect <- (c/(a+c))
  return(noDefect)
}
prec1=function(c,d)
{
  modDefect <- (d/(c+d))
  return(modDefect)
}
